    <name>
				<text>18.3.2.4 T Locate stationary points (copy)</text>
		</name>
    <questiontext format="moodle_auto_format">
				<text><![CDATA[<p class="HELM_exercise">Exercise</p>
<p>Locate the stationary points of</p>
\[f(x,y) = {@f@}.\]
<p>First find the partial derivatives of \(f\):</p>
<p>\(\displaystyle \frac{\partial f}{\partial x} = \) [[input:ans1]] [[validation:ans1]] [[feedback:prt1]]</p>
<p>\(\displaystyle \frac{\partial f}{\partial y} = \) [[input:ans2]] [[validation:ans2]] [[feedback:prt2]]</p>
<p>Now solve simultaenously the equations \(\displaystyle \frac{\partial f}{\partial x} = 0\) and \(\displaystyle \frac{\partial f}{\partial y} = 0\).
</p>
<p><b>Note:</b> write your answer as a set of points. For example, if you found the stationary points \((0,2)\) and \((1,3)\), your input should be <code>{[0,2], [1,3]}</code>.</p>
<p>Stationary points: [[input:ans3]] [[validation:ans3]] [[feedback:prt3]]</p>]]></text>
		</questiontext>
    <generalfeedback format="moodle_auto_format">
				<text><![CDATA[<p>We are asked to find the stationary points of \(f(x,y) = {@f@}\).</p>
<p>We begin by finding the partial derivatives of \(f\):</p>
\[\begin{aligned}
    \frac{\partial f}{\partial x} &amp;= {@ta1@} \\
    \frac{\partial f}{\partial y} &amp;= {@ta2@}
\end{aligned}\]
<p>Next, we find the points where both partial derivatives are zero. Note that each of them
    only depends on one variable, so that we can solve each equation separately.
</p>
\[\begin{aligned}
    \frac{\partial f}{\partial x} = {@ta1@} = 0 &amp;\implies x = \pm {@x1@} \\
    \frac{\partial f}{\partial y} = {@ta2@} = 0 &amp;\implies y = {@y1@}
\end{aligned}\]
<p>Therefore, there are two points where both partial derivatives are zero: \(({@x1@},{@y1@})\)
    and \(({@x2@},{@y1@})\). These are the <strong>stationary points</strong>.
</p>]]></text>
		</generalfeedback>
